				 Healthy rise in Satyam net
 OUR BUREAU				 	 Chairman Ramalinga Raju in Hyderabad on Tuesday. (AFP)																								Mumbai/Hyderabad, Oct. 23: Satyam Computer Services Ltd has posted a 27.92 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 409.09 crore for the quarter ended September 30, 2007 against Rs 319.81 crore in the corresponding quarter a year ago.																								The total income of the Hyderabad-based company increased 31.42 per cent to Rs 2,142.26 crore from Rs 1,630.11 crore in the year-ago period.																								Following the strong performance, Satyam has raised its guidance for the financial year ending March 2008 by almost 36 per cent in rupee terms and 42 per cent in dollar terms. It expects the earnings per share to increase to Rs 25.1. 																								The guidance reflects a positive business outlook. The company has recorded the highest growth in dollar terms in the past five to six years, chairman Ramalinga Raju said. 																								Acquisition spree																								Satyam today said it had acquired the UK-based consulting firm Nitor Global Solutions Ltd for $5.5 million in an all-cash deal. It plans to merge Nitor with its infrastructure management services business. 																								The company also signed a 10-year agreement with the UK-based Fujitsu Services to provide IT services to Reuters.																								Under the $1-billion programme, Satyam will provide infrastructure services for desk-side support, a global network operations centre and remote infrastructure management to Reuters.																								BPO arm																								Nipuna, the BPO services arm of Satyam, has been merged with the parent and renamed Satyam BPO Services Ltd. 
